						<tr>
							<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Stacking is non-blocking; the two are the same thing.  (thats the predominate way it was used in EQ1... but people would misuse it there as well.)  It is most clear if you think about discussions of haste/slow effects... where the spells/songs are commonly referred to as stacking, but the haste and slow component do not combine.  (bardic haste/slow had other side-effects that were valuable in their own right... not just for the haste/slow component.)
<br />

<br />
The main problem with stacking are/were when a conflict with one component of a multi-effect ability stopped the entire ability from landing.
<br />

<br />
In the above example, the correct usage would be to say that Elise's Ditty stacks with Merciless Melody; despite the fact that only the higher of the two agility bonus's took effect.  The other effects do combine.  
<br />

<br />
If the agility conflict caused the other effects not to take hold (i.e. the whole song was blocked), then that would be 'non-stacking'.  
<br />

<br />
(but I think its better to avoid using 'stack' in this situation at all, particularly when referring to the entire spell.)
<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">When 2 different buffs that give the exact same benefit but differ in strength are castable on a char at the same time but only the higher works (or in some worst cases in certain games, the 2nd one cast overwrites the first regardless of it's relative benefit) that is not stacking, that's just wasting Conc (or power, mana, whatever s relevant to that game).</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Unclear;  I would say they -do- stack though; the effects just do not combine.  In either case, the use of 'stack' alone is probably misleading and needs to be clarified with an additional information.  Alfetor has the correct usage.
<br />

<br />
If you were talking about 2 different multi-component buffs with predominately different effects, but one shared effect, and all of the effects take hold - except the shared one (of which only the higher of the two effects works) ... those spells would generally be considered to 'stack'.  (although you still probably want to qualify it.)
<br />

<br />
Just to reiterate:
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">The main problem with stacking are/were when a conflict with one component of a multi-effect ability stopped the entire ability from landing.</span>
<br />

<br />
----------------------------
<br />

