						<tr>
							<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Believe it or not, but there IS a whole world of MMORPG's out there, that are NOT EQ1. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Uh, sorry.  That makes no sense.  If you use a word that has a meaning in EQ1.... in an EQ2 discussion, then in the absense of any clarification, the understanding is you are using the EQ1 meaning.  Don't try to act as some kind of grammar police if you are trying to make people conform to some fly-by-night RPG of which you read the manual once in 8th grade, made 27 characters for, but never actually found anyone to play with.
<br />

<br />
Stacking is both abilties being active at once.  Thats why they refer to the SPELLS as stacking.  Because, they all pile up... right there on the spell bar for everyone to see.  They don't block each other, they don't over-write each other.  They... well, the spells stack.
<br />

<br />
Whether or not the individual effects combine... that needs to be handled on an effect by effect basis.  If you were to say something like <span style="font-style: italic">"The agility effect from Merciless Melody does not stack with the agility effect from Elise's Ditty"</span> then that statement is clear on what you mean.  That is very different from saying <span style="font-style: italic">"Merciless Melody does not stack with Elise's Ditty".</span></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
						</tr>
					</table></td>
				</tr>
